SIMPLE: inosculate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inosculate
<hw>In*os"cu*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inosculated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Inosculating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>osculate</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
unite by apposition or contact, as two tubular vessels at their
extremities; to anastomose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To intercommunicate; to interjoin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The several monthly divisions of the journal may
<qex>inosculate</qex>, but not the several volumes.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inosculate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inosculate
<hw>In*os"cu*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To unite by apposition or contact, as two vessels in an animal
body.</def> <rj><au>Berkeley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To unite intimately; to cause to become as
one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They were still together, grew⟦br⟧
(For so they said themselves) <qex>inosculated</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inosculation</ent>⟦br⟧
